In [[category theory]], a branch of mathematics, an '''opetope''', a portmanteau of "[[operation (algebra)|operation]]" and "[[polytope]]", is a [[shape]] that captures higher-dimensional [[substitution (algebra)|substitution]]s. It was introduced by [[John C. Baez]] and James Dolan so that they could define a [[weak n-category|weak ''n''-category]] as a certain presheaf on the category of opetopes.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Baez|first=John C.|last2=Dolan|first2=James|date=1997-02-10|title=Higher-Dimensional Algebra III: n-Categories and the Algebra of Opetopes|journal=Advances in Mathematics |volume=135 |pages=145–206|arxiv=q-alg/9702014|bibcode=1997q.alg.....2014B}}</ref>
